node.text:
Say hello to the vomer conch, arguably the owner of the greatest googly eyes in the ocean. These sea snails sit in the family Strombidae and are found mainly in tropical and subtropical waters. 

Known to marine science as Euprotomus vomer, these animals spend most of their time burrowed in the sand but will come out at night to feed. Their unusual eyes come in handy when predators are about, stuck on the end of long stalks which can move independently and poke out one at a time to see if the coast is clear.

Image credit: Sonja Ooms / Shutterstock.com

Cordulagomphus is an extinct genus of dragonflies that lived between 145.5 and 65.5 million years ago during the Cretaceous period. Characteristic features for these dragonflies include four large wings and two long antennae, as well as an elongated tail.

This particular fossil was found in the Santana Formation in Brazil, an Early Cretaceous rock formation that’s proven time and again to house remarkable insect fossils. Scientists have also unearthed pterosaurs, reptiles, amphibians, diverse invertebrates, plants and exceptionally well-preserved fossil fishes.

These hoodoos in Southern Utah are among the oddest geological structures in the American West's deserts, dating back over 100 million years.

A weathered rock column known as a "hoodoo" is formed when a thick layer of soft rock is covered by a thin layer of hard rock. When cracks in the hard rock allow the underlying soft rock to erode, one small cap of hard rock is resistant to cracking and protects the soft rock beneath. This protected rock cone eventually grows into a vertical pinnacle.

Say hello to the galaxy frog (Melanobatrachus indicus), a very rare species that belongs to the Microhylid frog family and is only found in India's Western Ghats. Named for its similar appearance to the night sky filled with billions of stars, it’s one of the most beautiful and uncommon frogs on the planet. 

It’s also tiny, about half the size of your thumb, so you’d be very lucky to see one in the wild!

node.text:
Fancy a dip? What you can see happening here is an example of bioluminescence, a chemical process which sees living organisms emit their own light. The result display glitters like the stars in the sky, and can shine in bright blue, green, or even red.

Bioluminescence seen among many marine organisms including fish, crabs, squid, and algae. It’s employed as a means of confusing predators, to attract prey, or lure in potential mates.

Blooms of tiny organisms such as plankton and worms can result in this kind of marine sparkle, lighting up when disturbed by movement from animals or the ocean’s waves. This is most common in the tropics, where warm, nutrient-rich water stimulates the growth of these small organisms, but it can also occur in cooler waters, such as Jersey Island in the United Kingdom or San Juan Island in Washington State.

Image credit: RugliG / Ting Cheng / Shutterstock

node.text:
Someone’s hungry! Check out this venus flytrap (Dionaea muscipula), a carnivorous plant who in this instance may have bitten off more than it can chew. In the wild, these plants are native to subtropical wetlands in North Carolina and South Carolina, United States, but they’ve become popular house plants across the world for their bloodthirsty behavior. Its survival is threatened by habitat degradation, and it is thought to be extinct in several of its native countries.

Venus flytraps use delicious nectar to lure in their prey. Its “mouth” is lined with trigger hairs and if one or more hairs are repeatedly touched, an electric charge shuts the trap causing its interlocking teeth to form a cage. The trap seals around the struggling insect before releasing digestive enzymes that dissolve the victim's soft tissues. It then absorbs the nourishing soup and, after approximately a week, reopens, with its previous victim’s hollow exoskeleton still in its mouth.

Did you know that Charles Darwin famously described the plant as "one of the most wonderful in the world”?

Image credit: Seb Haggett / @sebhaggett / Twitter

node.text:
An exciting visitor swept along the coast of Wales recently, as photographer and marine biologist Jake Davies captured footage of the elusive angelshark (Squatina squatina) in a world-first for the UK coastline. Listed as Critically Endangered on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, the angelshark has been in decline for the last 50 years but this sighting of a juvenile in a novel location could help to inform conservation efforts to secure their future.

A member of the Chondrichthyes, a class of cartilaginous fish that contains sharks and rays, the angelshark has a rather exotic body plan. Much like a ray, it has winged fins and a flat body which it can submerge into the sand for a spot of ambush predating. Like some species of shark, it has impressive jaws which it can project outwards at speed to snap up passing fish before they’ve had a chance to even clock they’re in danger.
